Will listen to anything you need to get off your chest :) I can’t provide solutions, but will try to help you find your own. I’m not a professional but I took a certification in basic psych and after my classmates completed the course with me, they were able to keep my demons at bay by practicing the active listening we learnt. I think… More we can all use a listening ear and I want to do my part. But... There’s lots of ethical concerns I can think of 1) I’m not a professional so how do I know if I’m out of my depth or if I become an excuse for someone not seeking actual professional help 2) I may have too much influence over people who open up to me 3) How do I keep myself safe I’d appreciate any ideas on how to resolve these and other issues I might not have considered or if I shouldn’t do this at all. Also, publicly asking for a listening ear is hard so any ideas on how people can identify themselves without publicising themselves?

A while back there was this post that was a bit unsympathetic towards leave voters who now seem to be shocked that brexit is not some kind of fairytale. I just want to say I really don't understand some of the comments. For example, the one starting with "Maybe if you stepped off your high horse to examine the harsh… More economic conditions of those who voted for Brexit". I, as an EU citizen, really don't have to be understanding of those people. Moreover, don't you think it's a bit offensive that you seem to be suggesting that because of someone's socio-economic background they wouldn't be able to make proper decisions. Adults are adults and they should be held accountable for their decisions. If they were children, they wouldn't be allowed to vote. In this world, we are judged by our decisions. It's perfectly fine to judge someone who voted for Brexit. It was their decision. Yes, politicians were misleading. But, ultimately, they were adults who made their own decisions and are now whining gloriously about it.

Why are gender identity and sexuality grouped under the same term 'LGBTQ+'. I say this as a gay man who is a supporter of the trans community. While both communities still have a long way to go in terms of equality, the LGB definitely has a lot more recognition and has received a lot more attention in recent years, whilst I feel it is… More much harder to be a member of the trans community in today's society. I worry that we hail LGBT progress when we are actually only really seeing progress for the LGB community and the trans community is being left behind. But because they all come under the same banner we forget about trans issues. Also sexuality and gender identity are two completely separate issues. Yes, gay people can support the trans community (and vice versa) but we will never truly understand what it means to question your gender identity. The label LGBTQ+ feels to me like "Oh these people aren't 'normal' let's shove them all under the same label".

I am an Indian international student, and going back to Delhi for this Christmas break was horrifically eye opening. No one is safe, I saw my peers studying in the best universities of the country get attacked, maimed and arrested by the police because they dared to raise their voices against an unconstitutional law passed by a… More fanatical governement. Parts of the national capital saw their internet getting suspended for days and Kashmir has been in complete lockdown for six months. Protestors have been killed by the police in Assam. Yet, I did not see this get the kind of international attention that other mobilisations on a similar scale have gotten. We are not talking about this enough and we have to, and Indians like me who have the privilege to study abroad need to bring our friends and peers from other communities into the fold. More importantly,our privilege and wealth hide the harsh realities that other Indians face which I only experienced first hand because it happened next door #caa#nrc

Topic: name of the Spanish and Latino American society As a Spaniard myself, I felt that the name was extremely awkward from the first moment I saw it. Hell, why does Spain need to have a preferent position with respect our American cousins? How would we, spanish people, feel if we had to sign in for the Argentinian and Hispanic… More society? Or Bolivian? or Chilean? and so on. Besides, It feels like it is some strange whistle to the imperial times that I personally find pretty distasteful and insulting for who are very own our brothers and sisters. Specially when there are words in our beautiful language to refer to all of us such as Hispanic or Latino. Lets remember that reggeton, Borges, la cumbia, Rubén Dario, del toro, el flamenco, García Márquez, Almodovar, and other excellent land marks of culture are as equally Chilean as they are Ecuatorian as they are Mexican, Cuban or Spanish. Let's get rid of this bullshit metropoli reference!
